      <hedline>
        <hl1>A War Over Rent, on Two Coasts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Steve Knight letter replies to Paul Krugman's June 7 Op-Ed column blaming rent control for housing problems in San Francisco</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While Paul Krugman and most of his fellow economists may believe that it is ''obvious'' that rent control reduces the quality and quantity of housing (column, June 7), their analysis ignores an important factor: price-controlled housing is often the only affordable alternative for low- and moderate-income city dwellers.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While Paul Krugman and most of his fellow economists may believe that it is ''obvious'' that rent control reduces the quality and quantity of housing (column, June 7), their analysis ignores an important factor: price-controlled housing is often the only affordable alternative for low- and moderate-income city dwellers.</p>
        <p>The federal government has largely abandoned its construction of subsidized housing over the last 20 years, and the private sector has consistently shown its preference for building new housing priced for the wealthiest 5 percent of our population. While the economists are probably right that eliminating price controls would stimulate construction, it's doubtful that much of this would be decent, affordable housing for the working class.</p>
        <p>Perhaps the answer lies in a combination of new governmental initiatives and tax incentives for private builders to increase the available housing supply for all income levels.</p>
        <p>STEVE KNIGHT  New York, June 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
